<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="gitlab-cicd">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>devops-engineer</domain>
    <summary>GitLab CI/CD is an integrated pipeline platform built into GitLab, configured via .gitlab-ci.yml. Use rules: for conditional execution and needs: for parallelization via DAG dependencies.</summary>
    <category>cicd</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>gitlab</tag>
      <tag>cicd</tag>
      <tag>pipelines</tag>
      <tag>dag</tag>
      <tag>deployment</tag>
    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>GitLab CI/CD</title>

    <summary>GitLab CI/CD is an integrated pipeline platform built into GitLab, configured via .gitlab-ci.yml. Pipelines are defined with stages, jobs, rules, and DAG dependencies (needs:). Use rules: (not deprecated only/except) for conditional execution and needs: for parallelization across stage boundaries.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>GitLab CI/CD co-locates code, issues, registry, and pipelines — eliminating cross-tool authentication overhead. The DAG via needs: cuts wall-clock time by running jobs as soon as their specific dependencies complete, not after entire stages finish. Built-in security scan templates (SAST, DAST, container scanning) require zero external configuration.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Project is hosted on GitLab (cloud or self-managed).</item>
        <item>Pipeline needs parent-child or dynamic child pipelines (monorepo).</item>
        <item>Team needs built-in container registry without external tooling.</item>
        <item>GitLab-native environments and review apps are required.</item>
        <item>Security scanning without external CI integration is needed.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Repository is on GitHub — use GitHub Actions instead (native integration).</item>
        <item>Organization already invested in Jenkins with shared libraries — migration cost may exceed benefit.</item>
        <item>Deployment target is exclusively managed by ArgoCD GitOps — push-based deploy conflicts with pull-based GitOps; trigger ArgoCD sync instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="pipeline-structure">
      <p>Stage/job organization, DAG via needs:, caching vs artifacts, workflow rules, and performance patterns.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use rules: instead of only/except for all conditional job execution.</statement>
        <rationale>only/except is deprecated and cannot combine conditions. rules: supports if/changes/exists combinators and per-rule variable overrides.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use needs: to form a DAG — jobs start when their specific dependencies finish, not after the whole stage finishes.</statement>
        <rationale>Stage-based execution forces serial stage gates. needs: allows test and lint to run in parallel after build, cutting wall-clock time by 30-60%.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep compiled outputs in artifacts, keep dependency folders in cache.</statement>
        <rationale>Artifacts are guaranteed delivery between jobs. Cache is best-effort and shared across pipelines. Mixing them causes missing dist/ in deploy jobs.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Workflow rules and default configuration">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
workflow:
  rules:
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == $CI_DEFAULT_BRANCH
    - if: $CI_MERGE_REQUEST_IID
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_TAG
    - if: $CI_MERGE_REQUEST_TITLE =~ /^Draft:/
      when: never

default:
  image: node:22-alpine
  tags: [docker]
  retry:
    max: 2
    when: [runner_system_failure, stuck_or_timeout_failure]
  interruptible: true
]]></code>
        <note>workflow rules prevent duplicate pipelines for push+MR events. Default retry covers transient runner failures.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="caching-strategy">
      <p>Scope cache keys with a lockfile hash to invalidate when dependencies change.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Scope cache keys with a lockfile hash to invalidate when dependencies change.</statement>
        <rationale>A stale cache with the wrong package versions causes intermittent test failures that are hard to reproduce.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Cache configuration with pull-push policy">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
cache:
  key:
    files:
      - package-lock.json
  paths:
    - node_modules/
    - .npm/
  policy: pull-push
]]></code>
        <note>policy: pull-push updates cache after install. Use policy: pull in downstream jobs that only read.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Caching dist/ or build/ output directories.</description>
        <reason>Built assets change every pipeline. Cache miss is expensive (re-download on every job). Use artifacts: paths: [dist/] instead.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="performance-patterns">
      <p>Parallelize independent jobs using needs: [] or needs: [specific-job] rather than stage ordering.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Parallelize independent jobs using needs: [] or needs: [specific-job] rather than stage ordering.</statement>
        <rationale>With stage ordering, lint waits for all build jobs. With needs: lint can run in parallel with other test jobs as soon as its single dependency finishes.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="DAG-based parallelization with needs">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
build:
  stage: build
  script: [npm ci, npm run build]
  artifacts:
    paths: [dist/]
    expire_in: 1 day

unit-test:
  stage: test
  needs: [build]
  script: [npm run test:unit -- --coverage]

lint:
  stage: test
  needs: [build]
  script: [npm run lint]
  # runs in parallel with unit-test
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set expire_in on all artifacts. Use 1 day for CI intermediates, longer only for release artifacts.</statement>
        <rationale>Without expiry, artifacts accumulate indefinitely. GitLab default is 30 days which fills storage.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="security-and-deployment">
      <p>Built-in security scan templates, protected variables, environments with review apps, and Docker/Kubernetes deploy patterns.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Include GitLab security templates via include: rather than writing custom SAST/DAST jobs.</statement>
        <rationale>GitLab-maintained templates stay updated with new vulnerability signatures. Custom jobs require ongoing maintenance.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="GitLab security templates">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
include:
  - template: Security/SAST.gitlab-ci.yml
  - template: Security/Dependency-Scanning.gitlab-ci.yml
  - template: Security/Container-Scanning.gitlab-ci.yml
  - template: Security/Secret-Detection.gitlab-ci.yml

container_scanning:
  variables:
    CS_IMAGE: $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHA
]]></code>
        <note>Override specific variables to point container scanning at your built image rather than the default.</note>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Mark all CI/CD secrets as Protected AND Masked in GitLab variable settings.</statement>
        <rationale>Protected limits the variable to protected branches/tags. Masked prevents the value from appearing in job logs. Both are required; neither alone is sufficient.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define environment: name and url on every deploy job, and pair with an on_stop job.</statement>
        <rationale>Environments enable deployment tracking, approval workflows, and rollback. Without on_stop, review namespaces accumulate and consume cluster resources.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Environment configuration with review apps">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
deploy-staging:
  stage: deploy
  environment:
    name: staging
    url: https://staging.example.com
    on_stop: stop-staging
  rules:
    - if: $CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == $CI_DEFAULT_BRANCH

review-app:
  stage: deploy
  environment:
    name: review/$CI_MERGE_REQUEST_IID
    url: https://$CI_MERGE_REQUEST_IID.review.example.com
    on_stop: stop-review
    auto_stop_in: 1 week
  rules:
    - if: $CI_MERGE_REQUEST_IID

stop-review:
  stage: deploy
  variables:
    GIT_STRATEGY: none
  environment:
    name: review/$CI_MERGE_REQUEST_IID
    action: stop
  script:
    - kubectl delete namespace review-$CI_MERGE_REQUEST_IID --ignore-not-found
  when: manual
  rules:
    - if: $CI_MERGE_REQUEST_IID
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable Docker BuildKit and use --cache-from with the latest tag to speed up image builds.</statement>
        <rationale>Without layer cache reuse, every build starts from scratch. BuildKit parallelizes layer builds and enables cache import/export.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Docker BuildKit configuration">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
docker-build:
  stage: build
  image: docker:26
  services:
    - docker:26-dind
  variables:
    DOCKER_TLS_CERTDIR: "/certs"
    DOCKER_BUILDKIT: "1"
    IMAGE_TAG: $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHA
    IMAGE_LATEST: $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:latest
  before_script:
    - docker login -u $CI_REGISTRY_USER -p $CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD $CI_REGISTRY
  script:
    - docker build
        --cache-from $IMAGE_LATEST
        --build-arg BUILDKIT_INLINE_CACHE=1
        --tag $IMAGE_TAG --tag $IMAGE_LATEST .
    - docker push $IMAGE_TAG
    - docker push $IMAGE_LATEST
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use when: manual for production deployments; use automated sync for staging.</statement>
        <rationale>Production requires human gate. Staging should be continuously deployed to catch integration issues early.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/build-node.yml" purpose="Node.js build job template with cache and artifact."/>
      <template path="templates/build-docker.yml" purpose="Docker build/push using dind and BuildKit."/>
      <template path="templates/deploy-k8s.yml" purpose="Kubernetes rolling deploy via kubectl."/>
      <template path="templates/deploy-helm.yml" purpose="Helm upgrade/install deploy job."/>
      <template path="templates/pipeline-full.yml" purpose="Complete production pipeline example (Node.js + Docker + K8s)."/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-generate.txt" purpose="LLM prompt for generating a complete pipeline."/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-optimize.txt" purpose="LLM prompt for optimizing an existing pipeline."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/"/>
      <link href="https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/yaml/"/>
